@phdthesis{Hall2021,
annote = {Objectives

To analyse whether including model performance or forecast skill metrics in the EFAS' notification criteria would improve its accuracy (in terms of hit rate):

* To find the most interesting      metrics to add value to notifications.
* To determine how to include      those metrics in the notification.
* To study spatial      variations.

Data

EFAS v4.0 data for its first 5 months operating (oct-2020 to april-2021).

* Lists of formal (72) and      informal (48) flood notifications.
* Feedback received from users      on formal notifications (8).

Methods

The selected model performance metric is the modified Kling-Gupta Efficiency (KGE). Not all notifications have KGE available, since there are areas where there aren't stations available.
The forecast skill is measured by the Continuous ranked Probabilistic Skill Score (CRPSS). The benchmark is the model's climatology calculated over 30 years. Skill is analysed for lead times from 1 to 10 days.
In both cases, notifications are clustered in 4 groups according to the 3 quartiles.

Results

Model performace:

* Formal notifications. KGE and      correlation are useful as discriminatory tool.
* Informal notifications. Bias      produces the most useful results.
* Formal+informal notifications.      None of the metrics (KGE or its constituents) show a clear trend.

The spatial analysis doesn't cast any interesting results, apart from a lower performance in Southern Europe related with lack of stations and highly regulated rivers.

Forecast skill:

* Increasing CRPSS at issued lead time is not useful for improving the hit rate.

The spatial analysis doesn't provide clear results either.

Conclusions

* KGE can't be used a notification criteria since it is not available in some areas (Italy and Greece).
* CRPSS avoids this problem, but, since it's only based on modelled data, it doesn't take into      consideration reality.
* It is suggested to add performance (KGE) and skill (CRPSS) labelling, rather than criteria. In the case of CRPSS it should show the skill for the same lead time as the      notification.

Further research

* Collect more feedback.
* Repeat the analysis with larger amount of data. Now there is 2 years data.
* Missed events haven't been analyzed. To do so, it would be necessary to spot flood events that weren't notified by EFAS (floodlist, etc.). Increasing the heat rate should not come at the expense of a higher miss rate.
* To consider the possibility of removing the deterministic requirement for EFAS formal flood notifications (is it still applicable?).

Comments

He only analyses precision, i.e., the true positive rate: TP /      (TP + FP). Optimising precision means that when the system sends a flood notification, indeed a flood occurs. This may lead to underpredicting floods, since missed events are not taken into account in the optimization. To avoid missing flood events, other criteria such as recall should be applied: TP / (TP + FN). A compromise between these two criteria would be F1 of Fbeta scores, which are a trade-off between them.},
