@article{Volpe2013,
abstract = {Understanding photosynthesis and plant water management as a coupled process remains an open scientific problem. Current eco-hydrologic models characteristically describe plant photosynthetic and hydraulic processes through ad hoc empirical parameterizations with no explicit accounting for the main pathways over which carbon and water uptake interact. Here, a soil-plant-atmosphere continuum model is proposed that mechanistically couples photosynthesis and transpiration rates, including the main leaf physiological controls exerted by stomata. The proposed approach links the soil-to-leaf hydraulic transport to stomatal regulation, and closes the coupled photosynthesis-transpiration problem by maximizing leaf carbon gain subject to a water loss constraint. The approach is evaluated against field data from a grass site and is shown to reproduce the main features of soil moisture dynamics and hydraulic redistribution. In particular, it is shown that the differential soil drying produced by diurnal root water uptake drives a significant upward redistribution of moisture both through a conventional Darcian flow and through the root system, consistent with observations. In a numerical soil drying experiment, it is demonstrated that more than 50{\%} of diurnal transpiration is supplied by nocturnal upward water redistribution, and some 12{\%} is provided directly through root hydraulic redistribution. For a prescribed leaf area density, the model is then used to diagnose how elevated atmospheric CO2 concentration and increased air temperature jointly impact soil moisture, transpiration, photosynthesis, and whole-plant water use efficiency, along with compensatory mechanisms such as hydraulic lift using several canonical forms of root-density distribution. ?? 2013 Elsevier Ltd.},
annote = {Objetivo:
Se presenta un modelo multicapa suelo-planta-atm{\'{o}}sfera con el objetivo de discernir los efectos simult{\'{a}}neos del aumento de la concentraci{\'{o}}n de CO2 y la temperatura del aire en la evapotranspiraci{\'{o}}n, la fotos{\'{i}}ntesis, el drenaje y la humedad el suelo.
La principal novedad del modelo es que incluye una representaci{\'{o}}n mecan{\'{i}}stica de la absorci{\'{o}}n radicular de agua y que optimiza simult{\'{a}}neamente los procesos hidr{\'{a}}ulicos y fotosint{\'{e}}ticos.

Teor{\'{i}}as e hip{\'{o}}tesis:
Modelo de absorci{\'{o}}n radicular del agua:
Aproximaci{\'{o}}n macrosc{\'{o}}pica que describe la planta como una red estructurada en la que cada capa est{\'{a}} directamente conectada al xylema. Calcula el flujo de agua en funci{\'{o}}n de los potenciales hidr{\'{a}}ulicas (cada capa del suelo, base del xylema, hojas y atm{\'{o}}sfera) y las conductancias (cada capa de suelo, xylema y estomas). Como resultado de ello se obtiene una formulaci{\'{o}}n de la transpiraci{\'{o}}n en funci{\'{o}}n de la disponibilidad de agua.

Modelo xylema-hoja ( fotos{\'{i}}ntesis):
Para describir la conductancia del xylema es necesario el potencial hidr{\'{a}}ulico de las hojas ($\psi$s). Para ello se formula la transpiraci{\'{o}}n en funci{\'{o}}n de la absorci{\'{o}}n de carbono; esta expresi{\'{o}}n se iguala a la primera de la transpiraci{\'{o}}n y permite el c{\'{a}}lculo del $\psi$s. 
De nuevo, la nueva expresi{\'{o}}n de la transpiraci{\'{o}}n requiere definir la conductancia de las estomas. Para ello se optimiza la ganancia neta de carbono (An) para un p{\'{e}}rdida de agua fija.
Se define tambi{\'{e}}n un modelo multicapa de atenuaci{\'{o}}n de la luz dentro del follaje.
Los resultados finales son la transpiraci{\'{o}}n (E), la tasa total de fotos{\'{i}}ntesis (A), y la eficiencia en el uso del agua (WUE = A/E).

Metodolog{\'{i}}a:
