@inproceedings{Moshe2020,
abstract = {Accurate and scalable hydrologic models are essential building blocks of several important applications, from water resource management to timely flood warnings. However, as the climate changes, precipitation and rainfall-runoff pattern variations become more extreme, and accurate training data that can account for the resulting distributional shifts become more scarce. In this work we present a novel family of hydrologic models, called HydroNets, which leverages river network structure. HydroNets are deep neural network models designed to exploit both basin specific rainfall-runoff signals, and upstream network dynamics, which can lead to improved predictions at longer horizons. The injection of the river structure prior knowledge reduces sample complexity and allows for scalable and more accurate hydrologic modeling even with only a few years of data. We present an empirical study over two large basins in India that convincingly support the proposed model and its advantages.},
annote = {Summary
The document presents HydroNets, a deep neural network for hydrologic forecasting that is designed to include prior knowledge about the subbasin structure into the network.
They present the results of two case/studies in the Ganga and Brahmaputra basins.

Methods
HydroNets has a direct graph structure in which each of its nodes contains three submodels that combine subbasin and basin information through temporal embeddings.
The combiner model is subbasin specific. It receives the static features and the temporal embeddings of the sources (upstream catchments) and it outputs a temporal embedding.
The shared model digests the output of the combiner model, and the temporal and static features and outputs a temporal embedding.
The prediction model is subbasin-specific and predicts the water stage/discharge from the temporal embeddings of the node.

Advantages:
* It reduces the sample complexity.

Future work:
* non-linear and recurrent submodels
* Prediction of discharge
* Addition of static features.

Results
The performance of HydroNets is compared against a baseline linear model in terms of R2 and R2-persist (a version in which the benchmark is not the mean, but the last record).
* When the depth of the graph increases, HydroNets is able to leverage information from deeper branches.
* HydroNets outperforms the baseline in all basins, but upstream basins are harder to predict.
* When reducing the amount of training data, the loss of performance in HydroNets is significantly lower than the baseline.
