@article{Bartholmes2009,
abstract = {Since 2005 the European Flood Alert System (EFAS) has been producing probabilistic hydrological forecasts in pre-operational mode at the Joint Research Centre (JRC) of the European Commission. EFAS aims at increasing preparedness for floods in trans-national European river basins by providing medium-range deterministic and proba-bilistic flood forecasting information, from 3 to 10 days in advance, to national hydro-meteorological services. This paper is Part 2 of a study presenting the development and skill assessment of EFAS. In Part 1, the scientific approach adopted in the development of the system has been presented, as well as its basic principles and forecast products. In the present article, two years of existing operational EFAS forecasts are statistically assessed and the skill of EFAS forecasts is analysed with several skill scores. The analysis is based on the comparison of threshold exceedances between proxy-observed and forecasted discharges. Skill is assessed both with and without taking into account the persistence of the forecasted signal during consecutive forecasts. Skill assessment approaches are mostly adopted from meteorology and the analysis also compares probabilistic and deterministic aspects of EFAS. Furthermore, the utility of different skill scores is discussed and their strengths and shortcomings illustrated. The analysis shows the benefit of incorporating past forecasts in the probability analysis, for medium-range forecasts, which effectively increases the skill of the forecasts.},
annote = {Objective

To assess statistically the skill of EFAS forecast during two years of data.

Data

25 months of forecasts: January 2005 – February 2007.
Comparison against a proxy of observed data: the simulated discharge using observed discharge.

Deterministic forecasts:
* DWD: 7 days
* ECMWF: 10 days

Probabilistic forecasts:
* ECMWF: 51 members {\&} 10 days.

Points with less than 4000 km² catchment area are excluded.
It analyzes lead times from 1 to 10 days.

Methodology

Threshold exceedance:
Forecasted discharge is reduced to binary events (flood or not) according to a exceedance threshold. These thresholds were derived from a long run of LISFLOOD with observed meteorology. There used to exist two thresholds: sever alert level (SAL) and high alert level (HAL). Given the low number of events, the study focuses only on exceedances of the HAL threshold.

Persistence:
They study the effects of persistence in forecast skill. They define persistence as:
* 2 consecutive forecast predict flood in the grid cell.
* In ensembles, more than a number of members above the threshold.

Skill score:
Characteristics that a skill score should fulfill:
* Equally representative regardless of the region or climate.
* As little as possible influenced by forecast bias (equitable).

Contingency tables were calculated for each river pixel with an upstream catchment larger than 4000 km². Out of these tables diverse metrics can be computed; the study uses a variety of skill scores:

* Odds ratio 
Odds = TP {\textperiodcentered} TN / (FP * FN)
It takes large values impeding comparison among different studies.

* Hanssen-Kuipers skill score: 
HK = TP / (TP + FN) - FP / (FP + TN) = POD – POFD -For extreme events such as floods, HK = POD = recall

* Frequency bias: ratio between predicted floods and actual floods 
FB = (TP + FP) / (TP + FN)

* Brier skill score: 
BSS = 1 – BSf / BSclim 
BS = 1/n $\Sigma$ (p – o)²

* Probability of detection (recall): 
POD = TP / (TP + FN)

* Frequency of hits (precision): 
FOH = TP / (TP + FP)

* Frequency of misses: 
FOM = FN / (TP + FN) = 1 – POD = 1 – recall

* Reliability diagram: it compares the forecast probability against the observed frequencies, so it identifies easily over or underprediction.
Results

Positive effect of persistence:

*Applying persistence reduces false alerts up to 70{\%}, whereas hits and misses are less affected. These changes disappear for persistence larger than 15 ensemble members.

* Increasing the total probability threshold reduces drastically false alerts, and slightly reduces hits and increases misses.

* Precision and recall are better for the probabilistic approach than for the deterministic, as long as the no. Members threshold is lower than 35.

* The frequency bias shows a general tendency to over-forecast. Values are lower (better) for the probabilistic approach and when the persistence criterion is included.

* The Hanssen-Kuipers score becomes recall in an unbalance case such as floods. The skill decreases steadily with lead time, with higher scores for the probabilistic approach and when persistence is NOT considered. From 30 members on, the scores are similar to the deterministic forecasts.

Reliability diagram:

For most of the no. members threshold, EFAS overpredicts. Some underprediction is observed when the no. ensembles threshold is also applied to the previous forecast.

Discussion

* DWD deterministic forecast renders lower skill than ECMWF deterministic.

* The equiprobability of meteorological ensemble members is not linearly translated into EFAS.

* In EFAS, the probability of a forecast is heavily conditioned on the previous forecast. Therefore, the interest in including persistence.

* The authors state the idea of treating deterministic forecasts as part of the ensemble probabilistic forecasting system by assigning them a weight to calculate a total probability.},
author = {Bartholmes, J C and Thielen, J and Ramos, M H and Gentilini, S},
doi = {10.5194/hess-13-141-2009},
file = {:C$\backslash$:/Users/casadje/AppData/Local/Mendeley Ltd./Mendeley Desktop/Downloaded/Bartholmes et al. - 2009 - The european flood alert system EFAS – Part 2 Statistical skill assessment of probabilistic and deterministic.pdf:pdf},
journal = {Hydrol. Earth Syst. Sci},
